    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-04-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-04-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="13"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d13">
                <head>13. Memorandum From Director of Central Intelligence Turner to the Chairman of
                    the Special Coordination Committee (Brzezinski)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d13fn1">Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs,
                        Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 55, <gloss target="#t_SALT_1"
                            >SALT</gloss>: Chronology: 3/25/77–5/9/77. Top Secret. Copies were sent
                        to <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> members.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-04-14">April 14, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Soviet <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s with <gloss
                            target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>s</item>
                </list>
                <p>1. At the <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> meeting on 7 April the question
                    was raised whether the Soviets would exceed a US-proposed <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> limitation of 550 launchers of <gloss
                        target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s in
                    the next few months.<note n="2" xml:id="d13fn2">For Brzezinski’s undated
                        memorandum to Carter summarizing this meeting, see <ref
                            target="frus1969-76v33#d158">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, vol. XXXIII, <gloss
                                target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> II, 1972–1980, Document
                        158</ref>.</note> The answer to the question depends on what rules for
                    counting launchers as <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed are agreed
                    between the two sides.</p>
                <p>2. Judging by the recent pace of the Soviet program, the number of <gloss
                        target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> launchers actually equipped with <gloss
                        target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed missiles is likely to grow fairly slowly,
                    in part because the Soviets have developed and are probably deploying both
                        <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed and single-RV versions of their new
                    generation <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s. [<hi rend="italic">3 lines
                        not declassified</hi>]. As you know, the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    has proposed counting rules [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not
                        declassified</hi>]. These rules would credit as <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1"
                        >MIRV</gloss>ed all boosters and launchers of types which have been
                    associated with <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>s in testing or
                    deployment. The <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> has also proposed that <gloss
                        target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> launchers be counted as <gloss
                        target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed when conversion is in initial stages.</p>
                <p>3. Our current estimate of Soviet <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed <gloss
                        target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> deployment this year, together with the
                    number of launchers which would be credited with <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1"
                        >MIRV</gloss>ed missiles under the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    proposals, is summarized in the attached table.<note n="3" xml:id="d13fn3"
                        >Attached but not printed.</note> The table shows that we expect the number
                    of launchers actually equipped with <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed
                        <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s to remain well short of 550 through
                    1977. However, under the combination of <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    proposals (i.e., the launcher and booster type counting rules <hi rend="italic"
                        >plus</hi> the proposal to count launchers under conversion) the Soviet
                        <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> launchers credited as <gloss
                        target="#t_MIRV_1">MIRV</gloss>ed would exceed 550 by October 1977. With the
                    counting rules alone, the number would remain below 550 through the year,
                    although it would be considerably larger than the probable actual Soviet
                    total.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TS_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Stansfield Turner</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Admiral, U.S. Navy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
